<tr><td><table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;">
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:52px 56px 40px;text-align:center;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 14px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.3em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.4);">YOUR COACHING TEAM</p>
  <h1 class="ht" style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'Cormorant',Georgia,serif;font-weight:300;font-size:42px;line-height:1.08;color:#F5F0E5;">The Team Behind <em style='font-style:italic;font-weight:400;color:#E8834A;'>LBTA.</em></h1>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-weight:400;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.45);">Who&rsquo;s on the court &mdash; and how they actually coach</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:36px 56px 0;"><p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Hey %FIRSTNAME%,</p><p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">I want you to know who&rsquo;s on the court. Not just their credentials &mdash; those matter &mdash; but how they actually coach. Because the person teaching your child (or teaching you) is the whole experience.</p></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:8px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#F5F0E5;border-radius:10px;border-left:4px solid #E8834A;">
<tr><td style="padding:20px 24px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 2px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:700;color:#1B3A5C;">Peter DeFrantz</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.4);">Director of Tennis Operations &amp; Growth</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.6);">USPTR certified. NCAA Division I at Lafayette College. 25+ years coaching, 4x Coach of the Year. Robert handles daily operations, scheduling, and parent communications. He coaches Adult Beginner on Saturdays, Adult Intermediate, LiveBall, and Cardio Tennis.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-style:italic;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">Teaching style: patient, methodical, detail-oriented. Especially effective with adult beginners and intermediates who want structure.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:8px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#F5F0E5;border-radius:10px;border-left:4px solid #C4963C;">
<tr><td style="padding:20px 24px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 2px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:700;color:#1B3A5C;">Peter DeFrantz</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.4);">Senior Coach</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.6);">USPTA and PTR certified. Played college tennis at Mt. San Jacinto, ranked #1 in SoCal. 8+ years coaching. Peter leads UTR Green Dot Competitive at Alta Laguna, co-coaches Youth Development and High Performance, and runs Adult Beginner and Advanced at LBHS.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-style:italic;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">Teaching style: competitive edge, high energy. Great for players who want to be pushed and for kids who thrive on challenge.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:8px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#F5F0E5;border-radius:10px;border-left:4px solid #2E8B8B;">
<tr><td style="padding:20px 24px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 2px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:700;color:#1B3A5C;">Allison Cronk</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.4);">Youth Programs &amp; Moulton Meadows Lead</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.6);">Allison leads all developmental youth programs at Moulton Meadows &mdash; Little Tennis Stars, Red Ball, Orange Ball, and Green Dot &mdash; plus Adult Bridge, LiveBall at Moulton Meadows, and the Saturday junior block at LBHS.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-style:italic;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">Teaching style: warm, energetic, structured. A favorite with younger kids and families. She has a talent for keeping 5-year-olds engaged for a full hour, which is harder than it sounds.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:8px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#F5F0E5;border-radius:10px;border-left:4px solid #1B3A5C;">
<tr><td style="padding:20px 24px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 2px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:700;color:#1B3A5C;">Andrew Mateljan</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.4);">Founder &amp; Academy Director</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.6);">Former ITF Futures professional. Peaked #3 SoCal and #12 nationally as a junior. Two-time Kalamazoo participant. Coached internationally for 7 years. Players coached include athletes ranked as high as ATP #133. D1 placements at South Carolina, Yale, and Cornell. Designed the LBTA curriculum system.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-style:italic;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">Teaching style: direct, technical when needed, always looking at the decision behind the shot. Teaches Adult Beginner, Intermediate, and Advanced at LBHS. Limited private lesson availability.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:24px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;border-radius:10px;">
<tr><td style="padding:28px 32px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#E8834A;">WHY THE COACH MATTERS MORE THAN THE DRILL</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">Here&rsquo;s something motor learning research shows that most people find surprising: <strong style='color:#F5F0E5;'>less frequent, higher-quality feedback produces better learning than constant correction.</strong></p><p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">A coach who talks less and designs better games will develop a stronger player than one who corrects every swing. Our coaches are trained to observe, design the right game for the moment, and give one specific piece of feedback when it matters &mdash; not a running commentary.</p><p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">That&rsquo;s why &ldquo;who&rsquo;s coaching&rdquo; matters more than &ldquo;what drills are they doing.&rdquo; The person on court shapes the environment. The environment shapes the player.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);"><strong style="color:#2E8B8B;">Try it:</strong> When you watch your child&rsquo;s class (or your own), notice how much the coach talks versus how much they play. Less talking usually means better coaching.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="mp" style="padding:24px 56px 0;text-align:center;">
